def distplot(data, col_name, hist_color="gray", kde_color="red", bins="auto", stat="density"):
    # plot histogram 
    sns.histplot(data[col_name], color=hist_color,bins=bins, stat=stat)
    # plot distribution on histograms
    sns.kdeplot(data[col_name], color=kde_color)
    plt.show()

Linear Correlation Control¶

Multicollinearity check is an important step in data preprocessing. It can lead us to better results when we get rid of multicollinearity.

Now we're going to look which features has correlation greater than 0.7 with any feature.

Skewness, Kurtosis and Z-Score Analysis¶

Statistical analysis can provide us better understanding. We may remove or correct some data.

Noone wants a data that has high skewness and kurtosis so we need to find them, if there is we need to fix them also.

In [19]:
def statistical_analysis(data, column, zscore_threshold=3):
    # calculate skewness
    skewness = skew(data[column])
    # calculate kurtosis
    kurt = kurtosis(data[column])
    # calculate Outlier count with Z-Score
    outlier_count = np.sum(zscore(data[column]) > zscore_threshold)
    # Print them out.
    print("Feature Number: {0}".format(column))
    print("Skewness: {0}".format(skewness))
    print("Kurtosis: {0}".format(kurt))
    print("Outlier count with {0} z-score threshold: {1}".format(zscore_threshold, outlier_count))
    print("="*40)

Splitting Data¶

We are going to split dataset into 3 set. These are train, validation and test set.

Explanation of Splitting Data¶

  • Train Set: We're going to use this set in model selection. We will use this data and we will decide which models are good enough to tune.
  • Validation Set: With the validation set we will tune our model. With hyper-parameter tuning, our model becomes more robust. If we won't overfit the validation set we can trust our model performance. And if the validation set not very different from the test set we can expect nearly the same scores in the test set.
  • Test Set: Finally! We're in final model development phase. We will use Train set to fit our data. And we're going to use hyper-parameters from validation phase. Then we're going to predict test set. We need to get similar scores that we achived in validation set. If we get little bad or little good it might happened because of data distribution and its OK. But if it's very bad then we overfitted to validation set.

In [23]:
def model_selection(X, y, classifier, scoring=None, cv=None, fold=3):
    # For sake of covering real data.
    Xt = X.copy()
    yt = y.copy()
    # Creating CV method.
    if cv is None:
        cv = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=fold)
    # We are creating evaluation metrics for selecting models.
    if scoring is None:
        scoring = {'roc': 'roc_auc',
                   'log_loss': 'neg_log_loss',
                   'acc': 'accuracy',
                   'f1': 'f1'
                  }
    # Apply cross validation and gather train - test results.
    cv_result = cross_validate(estimator=classifier, X=Xt, y=yt, cv=cv, n_jobs=-1,
                               return_train_score=True, scoring=scoring)
    # Use scoring keys for accessing scores/errors.
    # Train results
    train_roc_mean = np.mean(cv_result['train_roc'])
    train_log_loss_mean = abs(np.mean(cv_result['train_log_loss']))
    train_acc_mean = np.mean(cv_result['train_acc'])
    train_f1_mean = np.mean(cv_result['train_f1'])
    # Test results
    test_roc_mean = np.mean(cv_result['test_roc'])
    test_log_loss_mean = abs(np.mean(cv_result['test_log_loss']))
    test_acc_mean = np.mean(cv_result['test_acc'])
    test_f1_mean = np.mean(cv_result['test_f1'])
    
    return (train_roc_mean, test_roc_mean), (train_log_loss_mean, test_log_loss_mean), \
           (train_acc_mean, test_acc_mean), (train_f1_mean, test_f1_mean)
In [24]:
def multi_model_selection(X, y, classfier_list, scoring=None, cv=None, fold=3):
    # Metrics are in the same order that 'model_selection' function returns.
    metrics = ['roc', 'log_loss', 'acc', 'f1']
    # Create empty dataframe for results
    result_df = pd.DataFrame(columns=['Model_Name', 'Train_Result', 'Test_Result', 'Metric_Name'])
    # Run 'model_selection' function for every model
    for model in classfier_list:
        model_name = type(model).__name__
        model_result = model_selection(X, y, model)
        # We're transfering the results to Dataframe
        for result, metric in zip(model_result, metrics):
            result_df = result_df.append({'Model_Name': model_name,'Train_Result': result[0],
                                          'Test_Result': result[1],'Metric_Name': metric}, 
                                         ignore_index=True)
    return result_df

Tuning model¶

We're going to tune XGB and LGBM model. Because in model selection their scores better than others. With tuning model we will decide our final model for final model development phase.

After working with XGB I decided to not tune XGB because it takes too much time to fit data.

When tuning comes in we can think about grid search CV but we have so huge data. So actually we can split data and evaluate through validation data.

There is an another option too. We can combine our training and validation data then we can use Grid Search CV to optimize model parameters then selecting best parameters.

Because of huge data, using Grid Search CV with training and validation data will take good deal of time. So I will use splitted data.

In [30]:
def calc_metrics(y_true, y_pred, y_proba, verbose=True):
    roc = roc_auc_score(y_true, y_pred)
    loss = log_loss(y_true, y_proba)
    acc = accuracy_score(y_true, y_pred)
    f1 = f1_score(y_true, y_pred)

    if verbose:
        print("ROC Score: {0}".format(roc))
        print("Log Loss: {0}".format(loss))
        print("Accuracy: {0}".format(acc))
        print("F1 Score: {0}".format(f1))
    
    return roc, loss, acc, f1

def model_tuning(X_train, y_train, X_val, y_val, classifier, param_grid):
    # Store metrics for plotting
    # Roc Scores
    train_roc_scores = []
    val_roc_scores = []
    # Accuracy Scores
    train_acc_scores = []
    val_acc_scores = []
    # Log Loss Scores
    train_log_loss_scores = []
    val_log_loss_scores = []
    # F1 Scores
    train_f1_scores = []
    val_f1_scores = []
     
    grids = list(ParameterGrid(param_grid))
    
    for grid in grids:
        classifier.set_params(**grid)
        classifier.fit(X_train, y_train)
        # Train Prediction
        y_train_predict = classifier.predict(X_train)
        y_train_proba = classifier.predict_proba(X_train)
        # Validation Prediction
        y_val_predict = classifier.predict(X_val)
        y_val_proba = classifier.predict_proba(X_val)
        # Get metrics
        train_roc, train_loss, train_acc, train_f1 = calc_metrics(y_train, y_train_predict, y_train_proba, verbose=False)
        val_roc, val_loss, val_acc, val_f1 = calc_metrics(y_val, y_val_predict, y_val_proba, verbose=False)
        
        # Store metrics for plotting
        train_roc_scores.append(train_roc)
        val_roc_scores.append(val_roc)
        
        train_acc_scores.append(train_acc)
        val_acc_scores.append(val_acc)
        
        train_log_loss_scores.append(train_loss)
        val_log_loss_scores.append(val_loss)
        
        train_f1_scores.append(train_f1)
        val_f1_scores.append(val_f1)
    
    # For title in metrics
    metrics = ["ROC", "Accuracy",  "F1", "Log Loss"]
    # Storing
    train_results = [train_roc_scores, train_acc_scores, train_f1_scores, train_log_loss_scores]
    val_results = [val_roc_scores, val_acc_scores, val_f1_scores, val_log_loss_scores]
    # plotting result of train-validation results.
    # it will help us to determine which grid
    # is better or which grid overfitted
    plot_result.plot_validation(grids, train_results, val_results, metrics=metrics)

def plot_ROC(estimator, X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test, y_train_pred, y_test_pred):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=2, figsize=(10, 5), constrained_layout=True)
    ax[0].set_title("Train Set ROC Curve")
    fpr, tpr, th = roc_curve(y_train, y_train_pred)
    roc_auc = auc(fpr, tpr)
    ax[0].plot(fpr, tpr, 'b', label='ROC curve (area = %0.2f)' % roc_auc)
    ax[1].set_title("Test Set ROC Curve")
    fpr, tpr, th = roc_curve(y_test, y_test_pred)
    roc_auc = auc(fpr, tpr)
    ax[1].plot(fpr, tpr, 'b', label='ROC curve (area = %0.2f)' % roc_auc)
    plt.show()

def plot_conf_mat(estimator, X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=2, figsize=(10, 5), constrained_layout=True)
    ax[0].set_title("Train Set Confusion Matrix")
    plot_confusion_matrix(estimator, X_train, y_train, ax=ax[0], cmap="viridis")
    ax[1].set_title("Test Set Confusion Matrix")
    plot_confusion_matrix(estimator, X_test, y_test, ax=ax[1], cmap="plasma")
    plt.show()
In [44]:
def evaluate_model(estimator, X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test):
    estimator.fit(X_train, y_train)
    train_result = estimator.predict(X_train)
    train_proba = estimator.predict_proba(X_train)
    test_result = estimator.predict(X_test)
    test_proba = estimator.predict_proba(X_test)
    
    print("Results for Training")
    train_metrics = calc_metrics(y_train, train_result, train_proba)
    print("="*40)
    print("Results for Testing")
    test_metrics = calc_metrics(y_test, test_result, test_proba)
    plot_conf_mat(estimator, X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test)
    plot_ROC(estimator, X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test, train_result, test_result)
    return train_metrics, test_metrics

def univariate_fs(score_function, feature_count, X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test):
    # Create feature selector object
    selector = SelectKBest(score_func=score_function, k=feature_count)
    # Apply feature selection 
    X_train_transformed = selector.fit_transform(X_train, y_train)
    X_test_transformed = selector.transform(X_test)
    # evaluate model  and get metrics
    train_metrics, test_metrics = evaluate_model(tuned_model, X_train_transformed, 
                                                 X_test_transformed, y_train, y_test)
    # get selected features
    feature_names = X_train.columns[selector.get_support()].to_list()
    return train_metrics, test_metrics, feature_names
In [56]:
def store_results(result_df, metrics):
    roc, loss, acc, f1 = metrics
    result_df = result_df.append({"ROC":roc,
                                  "LogLoss":loss,
                                  "Accuracy":acc,
                                  "F1":f1,
                                  "Feature_Names":feature_names}, ignore_index=True)
    return result_df

So here is the deal. If we look closer to test results we can see 15 feature has % 73.29 accuracy and 10 features has % 70.7 accuracy. If we really really want same accuracy with full features which is %74.0 in test we should chose 15 feature model. But if we can say "OK % 3.5 will not cause problems." then we can pick 10 feature model.

If we are going to pick 15 feature model, we will drop 13 features. Now its % 0.46 reduced in dimensionality. Also there is no significant accuracy drop.

If we are going to pick 10 featuure model, we will drop 18 feature. Now its % 64 reduced in dimensionality. There is %3.5 accuracy loss.

What we could tried ?¶

  • We could try other univariate methods like f_classif and mutual_info_classif. Probably those functions will work as fast as chi2.
  • We could try Recursive Feature Elimination known as RFE. This function works recursively and eliminates features that you've selected in every step. It fits data in every step. This method will take some time.
  • We could also try Wrapper Methods. Wrapper methods actually uses another machine learning or deep learning model for selectingn features. You can easily observe RandomForestClassifier().feature_importances attribute after fitting process finished. With that option you can pick most k important features and use them in your final model. This can take time too.
